04069nam a22005295i 9780804782562DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202012cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047825627 a10.1515/97808047825622doi  a(DE-B1597)563900  a(OCoLC)1198930619  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHV5840.L4bM37 2012eb 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a363.450956922231 aMarshall, Jonathan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Lebanese Connection :bCorruption, Civil War, and the International Drug Traffic /cJonathan Marshall. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Middle Eastern and Islamic Societies and Cultures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Hashish, the Petroleum of Lebanon -- t2. The French Connection -- t3. The Intra Bank Connection -- t4. The Path to Civil War -- t5. The Civil War Drug Boom -- t6. The Syrian Connection -- t7. The Drug Melting Pot -- t8. From Narco-State to Failed State -- tAcknowledgments -- tappendix -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLong before Mexico, Colombia, and Afghanistan became notorious for their contributions to the global drug traffic, Lebanon was a special target of U.S. drug agents for harboring the world's greatest single transit port in the international traffic in narcotics. In the words of one American official, "certain of the largest traffickers are so influential politically, and certain highly placed officials so deeply involved in the narcotic traffic, that one might well state that the Lebanese Government is in the narcotics business." Using previously secret government records, The Lebanese Connection uncovers for the first time the story of how Lebanon's economy and political system were corrupted by drug profits-and how, by financing its many ruthless militia, Lebanon's drug trade contributed to the country's greatest catastrophe, its fifteen-year civil war from 1975 to 1990. In so doing, this book sheds new light on the dangerous role of vast criminal enterprises in the collapse of states and the creation of war economies that thrive in the midst of civil conflicts. Taking a regional approach to the drug issue, Jonathan Marshall assesses the culpability of Syria, Israel, and of Palestinian factions and other groups that used Lebanon as their battleground. On the international level, he documents Lebanon's contribution to the hard drug problem of major consuming countries, from the days of the "French Connection" through the "Pizza Connection," as well as Lebanon's unrivaled place in the global hashish market.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aDrug trafficxPolitical aspectszLebanonxHistory. 0aDrug trafficzLebanonxHistory. 0aPolitical corruptionzLebanonxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478256240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804782562423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804782562.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles